		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message27275303">"Good CGI is when you don't recognize it's CGI" - somebody in IRC, at some date I forgot<br />
<br />
This sums up my opinion pretty well on most sorts of animation techniques in general (including rotoscoping). When you can easily discern what comes from what, you're pulled immediately out of the story's immersion effect. This has a subtle but very noticeable impact on one's appraisal of a work. It can make a work feel cheap, artificial, or simply put, embarassing. The same goes for long shots intended to flaunt a technique or detail from a very high budget.<br />
<br />
Of course if it's a small occurrence in the overall work, then it won't make a difference save for being a very memorable moment to point and laugh at (or to close your eyes and pretend it doesn't exist). This is definitely something I recall from Seirei no Moribito for example, where they spend at least a dozen seconds showing really bad CGI from some sort of a water wheel when Balsa removes the hinge to get it revolving. Kemono no Souja has it pretty bad too when they CG animate the armies and Tohda. Now compare that to something like <!--link--><a href="http://www.nausicaa.net/miyazaki/mh/cg.html" rel="nofollow">Mononoke Hime</a>, which I didn't even realize it had CG until lpf pointed it out to me.<br />
<br />
It's a very easy way to cut corners these days, and its cost efficiency as well as its overall potential is absurdly high over traditional techniques. So long as animators are able to keep their productions consistently fluid with the rest of the landscapes, animation, whatever, I'm all for it. Unfortunately that's not always the case, but the technology is steadily improving so I'm still crossing my fingers for the future.</div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig"><div style="text-align: center;"><!--link--><a href="http://myanimelist.net/clubs.php?cid=40791">QD</a><!--center--></div></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
