		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message27275367">I agree wholeheartedly with nil. In fact, in recent times, CGI has become more prominent in shows such as ARS Nova which used CGI as its main animation technique. While it does make the battles look more exciting to look at, the stiff character animations make the whole experience so cringe-worthy and don't really add anything new to it. In other words, they could've easily just did it with normal hand-drawn animation and it wouldn't have made any difference at all.<br />
<br />
You could make the comparison that CGI is like what auto-tune is to music. There are ways to make both things work if you implement it in minimal doses to make something unique, but if you're just for the sole purpose emphasizing certain events it doesn't make really make it any special or distinct. Something like Shingeki no Kyojin did pretty well with just hand-drawn animation, until of course it went into some levels of CGI which looked pretty bad from the draw distance.</div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig"><div style="text-align: center;"><!--link--><a href="http://gonzonyan.wordpress.com/" rel="nofollow"><img class="userimg" data-src="http://i.minus.com/iFBKqTvDcfeI1.png" /></a><!--center--></div></div></td>
