		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message27335001">I'd just like to say that I was an ardent hater of the animation style in Arpeggio of Blue Steel at the beginning. It had the worst first impression for me of any show that season and the awkward movement of the human characters was a huge part of that. However, by the end of the show, I actually started to like it. I don't know if I just got used to it or the animation got better by the end, but I was pleasantly surprised at how the show managed to portray the kind of moè designs you'd expect from that kind of show with CGI without it being noticeable enough to take me out of the show.<br />
<br />
CGI also has tons of potential for making well-choreographed action scenes affordable on your typical TV anime budget, which <!--link--><a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fbTby6cyP9M&amp;feature=youtu.be" rel="nofollow">Majestic Prince</a> showcased many times this year.</div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig">&quot;My tables-meet it is I set it down<br />
