		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message27348571">CGI is a really "current state" based measure of subjectivity to it's quality, and in it's early conception was used more as a "wow" factor for novelty than actual stylistic use. <br />
<br />
For example, there's a scene that I remember from Golgo 13 the Professional where when I first saw it I actually said, "when the tech gets better, everything will be CGI. Note I said this, over 14 years ago, and I watched it on a VHS. In retrospect the quality of the CGI in that movie is bad. Really bad.<br />
<br />
When I did a few write ups of Aiura, I kept waxing poetic about the backgrounds being nice and well done, but there where a few instances of the dreaded "CGI vehicle" that glided along two dimensional road and looked suitably out of place.<br />
<br />
It happens, and it can be jarring if the quality of the CG is not to par with the rest of the animation, and any problems that arise are suitably related to budget and staff.<br />
<br />
It doesn't mean that CGI can totally be thrown out as a medium or effect, as (opinions ahead) Appleseed, Karas, Ghost in the Shell: Innocence, Wonderful days, etc, are still pretty good, or so I say.<br />
<br />
Even Zoids.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
