		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message27468415">The problem I have with most CGI use in recent TV anime is that they look so obvious that they often break the little immersion that is left.<br />
When it appears then I'm usually busy thinking about that use of CGI rather than focusing on what's happening on screen.<br />
Movies like the recent Harlock and Doraemon show that Japan starts building a CGI industry as well, maybe even similiar to western animation studios. But the use of CGI in a "classic" animation, especially on TV is usually used because they happen to be cheaper. Already modeled CGI models can be reused after creating it since it's only a matter of adjusting and moving the puppet instead of animating frame for frame. It's a bit scary considering that anime studios really lack the funds or just sales in general nowadays, and that they have to "cut corners" this way.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
