		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message27613941">I don't know about you guys, but I often notice CGI not because it looks terribly out of place, but because it looks better than the rest of the animation. While there are of course different types of CGI with varying qualities, the indicators for CGI(that I can think of) are primarily their perfect 3d proportions, perfect lightning and simple stiff shapes. The third point, if noticable, is usually what makes CGI cringe-worthy for me. The former two are not necessarily drawbacks beyond the fact that they might not blend. In fact it seems rather counter-intuitive to blame CGI for breaking immersion when all it did was to look noticably better than the rest of the animation.<br />
<br />
Of course, such is only the case with CGI of higher quality. Obviously, cheap budget-saving CGI may look bad, but one can argue that their hand-drawn counterparts may look even worse for the same cost.<br />
<br />
By the way, has anyone seen the CG in the new Code Geass? Skip to around 5 minutes or so.<br />
<a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=52avoSVwuvw" target="_blank" rel="nofollow"><a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=52avoSVwuvw" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=52avoSVwuvw</a></a><br />
Don't bully me for liking Code Geass.</div><div style="margin-top: 8px;"><em>Modified by superzarop, 01-11-14, 3:46 AM</em></div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
